>> There is a second form of Dependency Injection that uses setters instead of constructor injection. Do not use this form.
>Why?<p>Not using setter injection eliminates a huge class of bugs that occur when people try to use objects that haven&#x27;t had all of their dependencies injected yet:<p><pre><code>    $user = new RegisteredUser();
    // Any code that touches $user here will be bad
    $user->setEmail($email);
</code></pre>
> constructor injection can become a nightmare.<p>Which is why people use library to do it for them - an example for PHP <a href="https://github.com/rdlowrey/auryn" rel="nofollow">https://github.com/rdlowrey/auryn</a>.
